infodynamics.measures.continuous.kraskov
Class MutualInfoCalculatorMultiVariateKraskov

java.lang.Object
  infodynamics.measures.continuous.kraskov.MutualInfoCalculatorMultiVariateKraskov
All Implemented Interfaces:
ChannelCalculatorCommon, ChannelCalculatorMultiVariate, MutualInfoCalculatorMultiVariate
Direct Known Subclasses:
MutualInfoCalculatorMultiVariateKraskov1, MutualInfoCalculatorMultiVariateKraskov2
public abstract class MutualInfoCalculatorMultiVariateKraskov
extends java.lang.Object
implements MutualInfoCalculatorMultiVariate

Compute the Mutual Information between two vectors using the Kraskov estimation method.

Computes this directly looking at the marginal space for each variable, rather than using the multi-info (or integration) in the marginal spaces. Two child classes actually implement the two algorithms in the Kraskov paper.

Author:
Joseph Lizier
See Also:
"Estimating mutual information", Kraskov, A., Stogbauer, H., Grassberger, P., Physical Review E 69, (2004) 066138, http://dx.doi.org/10.1103/PhysRevE.69.066138

setProperty

public void setProperty(java.lang.String propertyName,
                        java.lang.String propertyValue)
Sets properties for the calculator. Valid properties include:
  • PROP_K - number of neighbouring points in joint kernel space
  • PROP_NORM_TYPE
    • - normalization type to apply to working out the norms between the points in each marginal space. Options are defined by EuclideanUtils.setNormToUse(String) - default is EuclideanUtils.NORM_MAX_NORM.
  • PROP_NORMALISE - whether to normalise the individual variables (true by default)
  • MutualInfoCalculatorMultiVariate.PROP_TIME_DIFF

addObservations

public void addObservations(double[][] source,
                            double[][] destination)
                     throws java.lang.Exception
Description copied from interface: ChannelCalculatorMultiVariate

Adds a new set of observations to update the PDFs with - is intended to be called multiple times. Must be called after ChannelCalculatorCommon.startAddObservations(); call ChannelCalculatorCommon.finaliseAddObservations() once all observations have been supplied.

Important: this does not append these observations to the previously supplied observations, but treats them independently - i.e. measurements such as the transfer entropy will not join them up to examine k consecutive values in time.

Note that the arrays source and destination must not be over-written by the user until after finaliseAddObservations() has been called (they are not copied by this method necessarily, but the method may simply hold a pointer to them).

computeSignificance

public EmpiricalMeasurementDistribution computeSignificance(int numPermutationsToCheck)
                                                     throws java.lang.Exception
Compute the significance of the mutual information of the previously supplied observations. We destroy the p(x,y) correlations, while retaining the p(x), p(y) marginals, to check how significant this mutual information actually was. This is in the spirit of Chavez et. al., "Statistical assessment of nonlinear causality: application to epileptic EEG signals", Journal of Neuroscience Methods 124 (2003) 113-128 which was performed for Transfer entropy.

Specified by:
computeSignificance in interface ChannelCalculatorCommon
Parameters:
numPermutationsToCheck -
Returns:
the proportion of MI scores from the distribution which have higher or equal MIs to ours.
Throws:
java.lang.Exception

computeLocalOfPreviousObservations

public abstract double[] computeLocalOfPreviousObservations()
                                                     throws java.lang.Exception
Description copied from interface: ChannelCalculatorCommon

Computes the local values of the implemented channel measure, for each valid observation in the previously supplied observations (with PDFs computed using all of the previously supplied observation sets).

If disjoint observations were supplied using several calls such as ChannelCalculator.addObservations(double[], double[]) then the local values for each disjoint observation set will be appended here to create a single return array, though of course the time series for these disjoint observations were not appended in computing the required PDFs).
